Against this, courts and state officials mounted partial resistance. A federal appeals court in San Francisco struck down Trump\'92s executive order ending birthright citizenship as unconstitutional, echoing earlier district rulings and reaffirming the Fourteenth Amendment\'92s guarantee. Other judges ordered the release of Kilmar \'c1brego Garc\'eda, a man wrongfully deported and then indicted on smuggling charges, and barred his immediate re-detention or deportation without notice. A coalition of twenty-one Democratic attorneys general sued to block restrictions on undocumented immigrants\'92 access to health and safety-net programs, warning of \'93significant disruptions.\'94 Another coalition of AGs urged Congress to ban masked federal agents, and House members demanded DHS disclose its policies on masks and unmarked vehicles. These actions did not dismantle the enforcement machine, but they showed that parts of the legal system still recognized the line between law and persecution.\
