While the coercive arms of the state were being sharpened, the civil service and regulatory agencies were hollowed out or bent toward private and ideological interests. The Environmental Protection Agency eliminated its research and development office and began laying off more than 3,700 staff, citing cost savings of $750 million. The State Department implemented a 48 percent budget cut and reorganization that stripped out programs focused on LGBTQ+ communities, maternal and reproductive health, and minority groups, and altered its annual human-rights reports to remove sections on those topics. The Supreme Court lifted injunctions that had blocked mass firings at State, allowing more than 1,350 employees to receive Reduction in Force notices. At the Department of Agriculture, a restructuring plan cut salaries and relocated thousands of Washington-based employees to five other cities, closing offices and weakening the department\'92s capacity to support farmers and food safety.\
\
Regulatory capture was most visible in the administration\'92s twin pushes on cryptocurrency and artificial intelligence. Trump signed an executive order creating a \'93Strategic Bitcoin Reserve and U.S. Digital Asset Stockpile,\'94 signaling that the federal government would begin acquiring and holding bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies. Days later, he signed the GENIUS Act, the first major statute regulating stablecoins, written largely to the industry\'92s liking. At the same time, Trump Media & Technology Group, a company he majority owns, announced the purchase of $2 billion in bitcoin, transforming itself into a crypto holding vehicle. Paul Atkins, a former adviser to crypto firms, took over as SEC chair and quickly dropped enforcement lawsuits against major crypto companies, including a long-running case against Ripple. The White House issued waivers allowing David Sacks, a special adviser on digital assets, to keep his crypto investments while shaping policy. Together, these moves fused public authority with private speculative interests in a way that made it hard to tell where governance ended and self-dealing began.\
\
In AI, the administration issued three executive orders that rewrote the field\'92s regulatory landscape. One order fast-tracked permitting for data centers and related infrastructure by dismantling environmental and land-use safeguards, revoking prior NEPA guidance, and instructing agencies to identify categorical exclusions for AI facilities. Another created an American AI Exports Program to promote full-stack U.S. AI technology abroad, tying export policy to a preferred industrial model. A third, titled \'93Preventing Woke AI in the Federal Government,\'94 required agencies to procure only large language models that met an ideologically defined standard of \'93truth-seeking\'94 and \'93neutrality,\'94 explicitly barring models that incorporate diversity, equity, and inclusion frameworks. These orders did more than speed construction. They embedded a particular worldview into the algorithms that will mediate public information and services, and they did so by executive fiat, with little legislative debate.\
\
The week also saw a reshaping of the tax and spending structure in ways that favored capital over labor and deepened inequality. On July 4, Trump had signed a tax bill that the Congressional Budget Office now projects will add $3.4 trillion to the national debt over a decade, while cutting Medicaid and food stamps by $1.1 trillion and leaving ten million more Americans uninsured by 2034. The law made permanent the corporate tax cuts from 2017, reduced corporate rates further, and eliminated credits for wind and solar development. A separate $9 billion rescissions package canceled $8 billion in foreign aid and $1.1 billion in funding for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, defunding PBS and NPR. Gene Sperling and other analysts noted that Republicans insisted the extension of tax cuts for the wealthy should not \'93count\'94 toward the deficit, even as they rejected similar treatment for Affordable Care Act subsidies, setting up large tax increases for working families. These choices did not merely reflect ideology. They re-engineered the fiscal chassis of the state to privilege investors and fossil-fuel interests while constraining the social safety net and independent media.\
