Information and media control formed the third major strand of the week\'92s pattern. The White House took direct control of press pool assignments, a role traditionally managed by the White House Correspondents\'92 Association, and promptly removed the Wall Street Journal from the pool covering Trump\'92s trip to Scotland after the paper published an alleged 2003 birthday letter from Trump to Jeffrey Epstein. The administration then barred the Journal from the pool altogether, while the New York Times and the Correspondents\'92 Association condemned the move as retaliation. Trump filed a $10 billion defamation suit against the Journal, Rupert Murdoch, and others, and separately sued CBS\'92s parent company, Paramount, over an edited interview with Kamala Harris, ultimately settling for $16 million. The FCC, under an administration-aligned majority, approved the merger of Paramount and Skydance Media after Skydance promised to eliminate DEI practices and address \'93bias\'94 at CBS News. At the U.S. Agency for Global Media, special adviser Kari Lake locked the acting CEO out of his email and systems and threatened the Voice of America director with removal unless he accepted a new position.\
\
These actions were reinforced by a campaign to delegitimize past reporting on Russian interference and to rewrite the narrative of 2016. White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt called for the New York Times and Washington Post to be stripped of their Pulitzer Prizes for that coverage. Trump told Republican lawmakers that Obama had \'93cheated\'94 in the 2016 election and instructed them to repeat the claim. Gabbard\'92s report, though it did not substantiate her allegations, was used to suggest that intelligence agencies had fabricated evidence against Trump. At the same time, the administration selectively released hundreds of thousands of pages of FBI files on Martin Luther King Jr. and additional documents from the Hillary Clinton email investigation, even as DOJ refused to release 100,000 pages of Epstein files. The effect was to flood the public sphere with archival material about long-closed controversies while keeping current networks of power and abuse in the dark.\
\
Artificial intelligence itself became a tool of manipulation. An AI-driven network of more than 400 bot accounts on X promoted positive messages about Trump administration figures, faltering only when asked to respond to the Epstein files controversy. Trump\'92s AI-generated video of Obama\'92s arrest blurred the line between satire and incitement, especially when shared by a sitting president. The \'93Preventing Woke AI\'94 order ensured that future government AI systems would be selected and tuned according to ideological criteria, not just technical performance. These moves did not yet amount to a full algorithmic state. But they marked a structural turn: data and models were being shaped to serve the regime\'92s narratives rather than the public\'92s need for accurate information.\
