Universities and civil society found themselves under new forms of pressure. Columbia University, after the administration froze more than $400 million in federal grants over alleged civil-rights violations and antisemitism, agreed to a $220 million settlement and a set of conditions that critics described as extortion. The deal imposed a partial mask ban on campus, placed an academic department under receivership, and required international applicants to answer specific political questions, all under the watch of an independent monitor. Around the same time, Columbia disciplined about eighty students for a pro-Palestinian library protest, imposing suspensions, revocations of degrees, and expulsions under a broadened definition that conflated antisemitism with criticism of Israel. America First Legal asked DOJ to investigate Johns Hopkins medical school\'92s DEI practices and to suspend its federal funding. These episodes showed how the threat of losing federal money could be used to reshape campus speech and governance, aligning universities more closely with the administration\'92s cultural agenda.\
