Yet resistance persisted. In New York City, Zohran Mamdani, a Muslim and South Asian assemblyman, won the Democratic mayoral primary on a platform of affordable housing and Palestinian rights, despite Islamophobic attacks and false claims about his citizenship. The Democratic National Committee reported record grassroots donations and volunteer sign-ups. In North Carolina, a Legislative Response Team tracked bills on immigration, DEI, and climate, and organized a protest against HB 958, a measure seen as a power grab that would undermine fair elections. In Durham, residents staged a rapid-response protest when ICE agents appeared at the courthouse. Climate activists in New York and San Francisco were arrested while protesting Wells Fargo\'92s abandonment of climate commitments under pressure from Trump\'92s fossil-fuel orders. These efforts did not alter federal policy, but they kept alive alternative visions of law and justice.\
