The Epstein saga, which threaded through many of the week\'92s events, illustrated how power now manages scandal. DOJ announced earlier in the month that it would not release more information from the Epstein files, after Bondi told Trump that his name appeared multiple times. At the same time, Trump ordered Bondi to seek the unsealing of grand jury testimony from the old Florida case, citing \'93public interest,\'94 and Bondi dispatched Deputy Attorney General Todd Blanche to interview Ghislaine Maxwell in prison. Federal judges in Florida and New York rejected DOJ\'92s motions to unseal grand jury transcripts, citing the narrow legal exceptions for such disclosures. In Congress, Speaker Mike Johnson shut down the House early for summer recess to block a bipartisan vote on releasing the files, even as the House Oversight Committee, under pressure from Democrats and three Republicans, voted 8\'962 to subpoena DOJ for Epstein records and to compel Maxwell\'92s testimony. Senate Republicans on the Judiciary Committee blocked the Epstein Transparency Act. Meanwhile, DOJ quietly released 240,000 pages of MLK files and more Clinton email documents. The result was a murky interplay of genuine oversight, self-protection, and political theater, in which the public could see just enough to suspect a cover-up but not enough to know the full truth.\
