In the background of these struggles, courts continued to draw lines that matter. A federal judge ordered the restoration of a public spending tracker website that the administration had removed, enforcing statutory transparency requirements. Another blocked Mississippi\'92s anti-DEI law in education, at least temporarily. Judges ordered the restoration of TPS and work authorization for tens of thousands of Haitians and required immigration judges to appoint counsel for immigrants with severe mental disabilities. The Muscogee (Creek) Nation\'92s supreme court affirmed citizenship rights for descendants of people the tribe had enslaved, enforcing an 1866 treaty. These rulings did not reverse the week\'92s broader drift, but they showed that the legal order still contains pockets of resilience.\
\
By week\'92s end, the Democracy Clock remained at 7:57 p.m., but the meaning of that hour had thickened. The executive branch had taken further steps to turn law enforcement into a tool of politics, to hollow out or capture agencies meant to serve the public, and to manage the information environment through lawsuits, access control, and algorithmic standards. Immigration and homelessness were recast as security problems to be met with detention, surveillance, and civil commitment, rather than as questions of rights and welfare. Universities and media organizations were reminded that their funding and mergers depend on ideological compliance. Courts and civil society pushed back in places, preserving birthright citizenship, some immigrant protections, and slices of transparency. Those acts of resistance kept the clock from jumping forward. But they did not move it back.\
\
The significance of this week lies in how normalized these patterns have become. A DOJ strike force aimed at a former president, a bitcoin reserve that dovetails with the president\'92s private holdings, an AI order that encodes ideology into procurement, a press pool controlled from the West Wing, a clean-water grant canceled as \'93wasteful DEI\'94\'97each would once have been a major scandal. Taken together, they now form the background noise of governance. The Civic Covenant, as the moral analysis suggests, still holds in places, but its fractures in restraint, stewardship, and truthfulness are widening. At 7:57 p.m., there is still time on the clock. Yet with each week like this one, the work required to repair the damage grows, and the distance between formal democracy and its lived reality narrows further.\
